            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Thomas Riley\u2019s life has been an exercise in curating space, both personal and professional. The son of a Palo Alto librarian and an architect, he grew up in a home where structure and narrative were twin religions. While he absorbed his father\u2019s appreciation for clean lines and his mother\u2019s love for stories, he felt a pull towards the chaotic energy of San Francisco, a city that defied the manicured order of his suburban youth.\n\nHis educational path was unconventional for an arts director. Forsaking art history, Thomas earned a Master's in Urban Planning from UC Berkeley, fascinated by how cities shape human interaction. He spent his twenties in a thankless city planning job, feeling creatively stifled by bureaucracy. The dot-com bust of the early 2000s, which resulted in his layoff, became his greatest liberation. He began volunteering at a small, struggling gallery in the Mission, and discovered his true calling. He wasn't just hanging art; he was using his planning skills to design experiences, guiding viewers through a space with an intentional, story-driven flow.\n\nThis newfound passion coincided with the quiet end of his marriage. His ex-wife, a pragmatic software engineer, couldn\u2019t understand his pivot to a world of financial uncertainty and subjective value. After the divorce, Thomas poured himself entirely into his work. Today, at 49, he is the director and chief curator of \"Proxemic Arts,\" a respected contemporary gallery in Hayes Valley. His life is a testament to his dedication; he lives in a minimalist loft directly above the gallery, making his commute a simple walk down a flight of stairs.\n\nHis days are a blend of solitude and intense social engagement. Mornings are for quiet contemplation and coffee overlooking the silent gallery floor, while evenings are often spent hosting openings, charming collectors, and mentoring the challenging, brilliant artists he represents. His social circle is his professional one. He hopes to one day create an endowment for emerging Bay Area artists, ensuring his legacy is not in the art he sold, but in the careers he helped build. For Thomas, San Francisco is the ultimate gallery, and his work is his singular, focused contribution to its ever-changing exhibition."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers the beige conference room, the HR rep\u2019s rehearsed sympathy. But the true memory is stepping outside onto Montgomery Street, clutching a cardboard box of office supplies after his layoff in 2002. The dot-com bust had just erased his career. Instead of dread, a thrilling, terrifying lightness flooded him. The city\u2019s rigid grid suddenly felt like an open map. It wasn't an ending; it was the demolition before a true foundation could be laid. That day, he learned that losing a prescribed structure could be the only way to build a meaningful one.\n\n2.\nIt was a sweltering afternoon in the underfunded Mission gallery, around 2003. He was wrestling a jagged metal sculpture by a new artist. He moved it three feet to the left, and suddenly, the entire room breathed differently. The path to the other paintings became a journey, not a line. It was a revelation, a jolt of pure clarity. All his years studying urban flow weren\u2019t wasted; they were for this. He wasn't just hanging art; he was designing desire and directing the human gaze. It was urban planning, but with a soul.\n\n3.\nThe end of his marriage wasn't a fight, but a quiet conversation in their empty dining room. His ex-wife, Sarah, looked at his hands, calloused from hanging wire and spackling walls. \u201cI just don\u2019t understand the return on this investment, Tom,\u201d she said, her voice full of genuine, pragmatic concern. In that moment, he saw the unbridgeable gulf between them. Her world was quantifiable; his was now about intangible impact. The sadness was profound, but it cemented his resolve. He had chosen a life that couldn't be measured on a spreadsheet.\n\n4.\nHe remembers standing in the back of his own gallery, Proxemic Arts, on its first opening night nearly fifteen years ago. The Hayes Valley space was humming with voices, the scent of wine, and possibility. He watched a couple pause exactly where he\u2019d intended, caught by the sightline he had engineered between two seemingly unrelated pieces. It was the opposite of his old city job. This wasn't bureaucracy; it was living architecture, a conversation he had designed. For the first time, he felt he truly belonged in San Francisco.\n\n5.\nJust last week, holding his first coffee, he stood at the railing of his loft, looking down into the silent gallery below. The morning light cut across the polished concrete floor, illuminating the stark forms of the current installation. This was his commute. This quiet observation, the calm before the city woke and the doors opened, was his reward. It was the perfect synthesis of his parents\u2019 legacies: the clean, architectural space filled with potent, unspoken stories. In this solitude, his life felt curated, complete, and utterly his own."
        },
